To generate a table of contents in a LaTeX document, you need to use the `\tableofcontents` command. Here's a simple example:

```latex
\documentclass{article}

% Compile the document at least twice to ensure the ToC is updated
% LaTeX runs: pdflatex (or xelatex, lualatex) file.tex, pdflatex file.tex

\begin{document}

% Title and abstract (optional)
\title{Sample Document with Table of Contents}
\author{Your Name}
\maketitle

% Optional abstract
%\begin{abstract}
%This is a brief summary of the document.
%\end{abstract}

% Start the content section
\section{Introduction}
This is the introduction. It will appear as the first section in the ToC.

\section{Methodology}
Here, we discuss the methods used. This section will also be listed in the ToC.

\subsection{Data Collection}
A sub-section under Methodology, also included in the ToC.

\section{Results}
The findings are presented in this section.

\subsection{Analysis of Data}
A detailed look at the results, with automatic ToC entry.

\section{Conclusion}
We summarize the document and suggest future work.

% Generate the Table of Contents
\tableofcontents

% Note: The \tableofcontents command should be placed where you want the ToC to appear.
% Typically, it's after the front matter (title, abstract, etc.) but before the main content.

% The document continues, but for this example, we conclude here.

\end{document}
```

When you compile this LaTeX document, LaTeX will read the sections and subsections you've created and automatically generate a table of contents based on those headings, with appropriate page numbers. Remember to compile your document twice to ensure the table of contents is correctly updated with the page numbers.

